object.field:
I had an incredible time making this winter landscape. I used pastels covered with corn husks for the sky and was very pleased with the contrast of the mountains in the background. The cabin with smoke rising from the chimney made me want to enter it and sit by the fire. I could clearly imagine sitting in the cabin and enjoying the landscape and oneness with nature from a window. It definitely brought out my oneness with nature. I hope it does the same for you!
Botanical materials included poplar, blackberry, day lilly, lilly of the valley and assorted Fall leaves; straw, corn husks, fern, hydrangea stems, onion skins, cosmos, cotton and birch bark.

This colorful sunset was made almost completely from brightly colored Fall leaves. While the sky used whole leaves, the shimmering water required hundreds of tiny strips of leaves. This landscape reminds me of the magnificent sunsets which I have enjoyed while vacationing in the Caribbean. I find it very inviting and hope you do too.
Botanicals include: Fall leaves of various colors, poplar leaves, skeleton leaf, ornamental cabbage, fern and pieces of beehive.

This colorful garden scene with bright birds above can’t help but make you smile. Can you feel the warm sunshine on your face on this beautiful sunny day?
Botanicals include: Astilbe, larkspur, pampas grass blossoms, thryallis, salvia, buttercups, veronica, pansy, baby’s breath, gerbera daisy, fern, browned lily leaves, straw, blackberry leaves and assorted leaves.

Everyone loves a seascape – especially when you live in the Finger Lakes. The sky was made from hydrangea and the water from delphinium and onion membrane. The yellow and orange sails on the boats were made from straw. The red and green sails were made from poinsettia. The wooden boats were from browned lily leaves. The sand was made from a variety of faded lily leaves. Other botanicals include: ixora, yarrow, allium, deutzia, moss and miscellaneous leaves.

This regal rooster has generated a lot of crowing and clucking. I love roosters and had wanted to create one with pressed flowers for some time. I must admit that I hadn’t planned for him to be so large. The rooster was made with hollyhock petals, gerbera daisy, pampas grass blossoms and tree bark. The barnyard and coop were made with lily of the valley leaves, butterfly weed, goldenrod, fall leaves, ornamental grass blossoms, browned daylily leaves, poplar leaves, straw, ornamental cabbage. The sky was created from the back side of poplar leaves. Wouldn’t you love to take this Regal Rooster home with you?

This piece was very fun to create and even more fun to share with customers.
Botanicals included hydrangea, lily of the valley leaves, buttercups, larkspur, speedwell, astilbe, golden alexander, geranium, cora bell, primrose, rose, peony, forget me nots, lambs ear and various greens.

Don’t you love waterfalls? Can you hear the roar of the water as it cascades down from above?
Botanicals include: Japanese maple leaves, fern, skeleton leaves, blackberry leaves, maidenhair fern, goldenrod, smoke bush leaves and cotton.

I learned the art of creating birch trees at a recent conference hosted by the World Wide Pressed Flower Guild. I used real birch bark and added pieces of other botanicals to make them appear realistic. To depict summertime, I added many strips and cuttings of green and brown leaves and added colorful flowers. The birds were made from banana peel. Wouldn’t it be fun to take a walk through the woods?
Botanicals include: birch bark, miscellaneous green, brown and grey leaves, fern, Queen Anne’s lace, Cora bell, forget-me-nots, garlic skin and banana peel.

Can you feel the sun shining and the wonderful scent of flowers in bloom. The peaceful parrot and toucan are an added treat. Botanicals include oxora, geranium, yarrow, deutzia, maidenhair and various fern leaves, moss and various flower petals gathered while vacationing in the Caribbean. The sky and the walkway were colored using pastels.

Wagons always remind me of my childhood. This wagon was created with fall leaves, straw (dyed green) and yellow daisies. It is filled with a vast bouquet of blossoms and greens. I hope it brings a smile to your face.
Botanicals include: Fall leaves, straw, daisies, sunflower, delphinium, scabiosa, geranium, salvia, hydrangea, maidenhair fern, rose petals and silver poplar.

I was introduced to using beehive material from a dear friend from the UK. I just love the swirls for flower baskets.
Botanicals include: hydrangea, cosmos, hellebore, scabiosa, salvia, deutzia, bleeding heart, wild onion tendrils, ivy, and astilbe leaves.

Many of the flowers displayed in this floral wheelbarrow came from a friend in Anaheim, California. The wheelbarrow itself was made from the underside of blackberry leaves and straw (dyed blue) with a cosmos wheel.
Botanicals include: Blackberry leaves, straw, cosmos, bridal veil, hydrangea, lily, Mexican bird of paradise, scabiosa, bridal veil solidago, pansy and maidenhair fern.

I love peonies, especially the dark red varieties. This piece features a vase created with a magnolia leaf gathered during a vacation in Nashville, TN which is adorned with a fiddlehead fern. The vase is filled with peony, delpinium, scabiosa, larkspur, sage leaves, speedwell, Queen Anne’s lace, cora bell leaves and wild onion tendrils. The vase sits on ginkgo leaf. The table was made from browned day lily leaves. The background is decorative paper.

Spring is the time of new awakenings in my garden. I especially love when the daffodils poke through the ground and show their bright yellow heads. All seems well in the world.
Botanicals include: daffodils, wild onion tendrils, lily of the valley leaves, larkspur petals and Artemisia.

This lovely picture was made under the guidance of an award-winning pressed flower artist from Taiwan. She taught me how to emphasize the light both in the pastel background and by placing darker flower petals and dyed skeleton leaves on top of lighter petals. It was a very “enlightening” class!
Botanicals include: gerbera daisy, ivy, skeleton leaves and various leaves.

This colorful collage features Japanese maple leaves of various shades along with sea oats layered between sheets of Japanese Sanwa paper. The background is handmade rice paper. I love the colors and the motion in this simple design. I hope you do too!

I learned how to press straw a few years ago but up until now only used it to make birdhouses, window sills and other simple designs. This design was made with 100% pressed straw. The bird was designed with strips of straw with added cuttings to enhance this fine feathered friend. The flowers and leaves, however, were much more complex to make. They were made from pieces which were cut and angled to reflect the veins in a leaf and to add dimension to the flower petals. A lot more effort went into this design than one might have thought. I hope you like it!
Botanicals include: straw, straw & more straw, some of which were dyed.

Did you know that birch bark consists of two layers? Just under the outer gray/off white layer is this lovely speckled tan bark which makes a lovely flower basket. The beautiful orchid was from a Mother’s Day bouquet from my son and his wife. The table was made from smoke bush leaves gathered in the Fall. I hope you like it!
Botanicals include: birch bark, orchid, delphinium, dogwood, roses, deutzia, Japanese lace maple, ivy and clematis leaves.
